@ericabrescia a simple example

on slide 2 he relies on the fact that there are 10,000 crypto currencies to strengthen the claim on energy consumption. 

on slide 4, he chooses the one with the slowest throughput when making a claim about tx rate.

@mave99a yes and i mention it in the article. we borrow some ideas from AP's design.

the one thing we do differently is put the name (identity) on-chain.

very important for ux because you can control your identity while delegating your entire client experience to a managed service.

@benedictevans @sriramk assume each user only stores first order actions like "i follow x" and "i liked y"

you can write a crawler that ingests everything, and exposes an api to query across multiple degrees

actions are cryptographically signed, so you can verify each crawler response if you want

@benedictevans @sriramk good point. 

the visible signals - reactions, shares and follows - are baked into the protocol and stored alongside the message.

invisible signals like viewing time may be proprietary to each client, but this might be "good enough" for a recommendation system.

@benedictevans @sriramk Blocking and promotion isomorphic at some level.  

The network chooses if and when you see something, because they have a monopoly on user data, and by extension, distribution.

If you don‚Äôt like their choice, well that's too bad.

@Suhail email hasn't just been slow, it's basically static.

the real reason is not that it's hard, but that it is far more profitable to improve email clients than it is to improve email itself. 

the right answer might be to find ways to reward people for making useful protocol changes

@Suhail in markets with network effects: 

centralized product ‚Üí  rent-seeking centralized monopolist with unhappy users (e.g. most social media)

decentralized protocol ‚Üí competitive, centralized company with happier users (e.g. email, browsers)

@benedictevans storing your life savings in a key is not a desirable state for most (like running an email server under your desk)

but being able to to do that makes it easy to exit or switch "hosting providers" at any time.

i think this is an underrated superpower of crypto networks.

@daltonc identifying pmf early is surprisingly hard for most people, unless they've seen it happen before. 

the less you know about what success really looks like , the more you rotate on founder status, investors and press.

wonder if there's a way to compress the learning curve?
